{"expireTime":9007200854063645000,"key":"transformer-remark-markdown-html-c94cf4ea67e16b2664f1d00de886995b-gatsby-remark-imagesgatsby-remark-embed-youtubegatsby-remark-responsive-iframegatsby-remark-prismjsgatsby-remark-copy-linked-filesgatsby-remark-smartypants-","val":"<p>So the other day I discovered a little talked about object in Cinema 4D that I believe deserves more credit. Up until now, my workflow for my 3D animations has been:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Create a scene</li>\n<li>Fly a camera through it</li>\n<li>Render it</li>\n<li>Create a new camera/fly through</li>\n<li>Render it</li>\n<li>Repeat until desired shots are met</li>\n<li>Then use Final Cut Pro to edit the renders together.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>One time I tried a new system, that kind-of worked; I created a camera, made my moves in order with one-frame camera moves that flew my camera to the next angle. I say kind-of because the extreme moves and bezier splines caused “rubber-banding”, where the camera becomes unpredictable. I knew there had to be a better way.</p>\n<p>Introducing the Stage object. Accessed through the Object -> Scene menu, the Stage object allows you to drop in multiple cameras, skies, backgrounds, foregrounds and environments, key-framed in at certain times in your timeline. To use insert the stage object into your Object Manager by selecting it in the Object -> Scene menu.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 582px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/81c4691e15ccdcd8e788e987b78ac94e/14007/stage-object-1.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 83.1081081081081%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"stage object 1\"\n        title=\"stage object 1\"\n        src=\"/static/81c4691e15ccdcd8e788e987b78ac94e/14007/stage-object-1.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/81c4691e15ccdcd8e788e987b78ac94e/a80bd/stage-object-1.jpg 148w,\n/static/81c4691e15ccdcd8e788e987b78ac94e/1c91a/stage-object-1.jpg 295w,\n/static/81c4691e15ccdcd8e788e987b78ac94e/14007/stage-object-1.jpg 582w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 582px) 100vw, 582px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>At your first desired camera in-point (probably frame 0) drag your first camera into the “Camera” Field in the Stage Attributes. Create a new keyframe by right-clicking (or Ctrl+clicking on a Mac) on the keyframe icon next to the Camera Attribute (it should turn red).</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 564px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/5e609b8dd930e8f0a290948e2d824baf/7723c/stage-object-2.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 42.567567567567565%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"stage object 2\"\n        title=\"stage object 2\"\n        src=\"/static/5e609b8dd930e8f0a290948e2d824baf/7723c/stage-object-2.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/static/5e609b8dd930e8f0a290948e2d824baf/a80bd/stage-object-2.jpg 148w,\n/static/5e609b8dd930e8f0a290948e2d824baf/1c91a/stage-object-2.jpg 295w,\n/static/5e609b8dd930e8f0a290948e2d824baf/7723c/stage-object-2.jpg 564w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 564px) 100vw, 564px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Go on down your timeline to your next shot and drag the second camera into the Camera Field in the Stage Attribute. Right click (or Ctrl+clicking on a Mac) on the keyframe icon next to the Camera Attribute to create a new keyframe for Camera-Dos!</p>\n<p>Repeat for as many shots as desired.</p>\n<p>It is important to note that these keyframes work the same as “hold” keyframes in After Effects, not standard keyframes, meaning there will be no “tweening” between the cameras, just a cut.</p>"}